summary: Marked the 9/11 anniversary, honored victims and first responders, and renewed commitment to supporting heroes and maintaining community and national resilience in the face of terror. Also warned of the dangers of violent extremism highlighted by the October 7th attack and committed to supporting efforts to protect citizens and address consequences such as hostage situations. Led a letter urging the Department of Transportation to allocate $36 million for upgrades to the Philadelphia TRACON STARS air traffic control system to address recurring communication and radar outages that threaten pilot and passenger safety and reliability of operations. Condemned the use of a military installation (Joint Base McGuire-Dix-Lakehurst) as an immigrant detention center as an inappropriate politicization of defense resources that jeopardizes military preparedness and could enable ICE raids in New Jersey communities. Co-led a July 29, 2025 letter with Rep. Herb Conaway Jr. and other Members pressing Defense and DHS for transparency and briefings on the plan to house undocumented immigrants at JBMDL, stressing that mission readiness must not be compromised and seeking details on operations, funding, detainee care, and coordination with local authorities. Also secured community project funding to upgrade a local firehouse HVAC system and other public-safety related infrastructure to strengthen local emergency response capabilities and public safety. Recently appointed to the House Armed Services Committee, he intends to work in a bipartisan manner on the committee to support the base, improve military readiness, oversee defense policy and spending, and advocate for the safety and needs of service members both at home and abroad. The congressman's new Chief of Staff, Keith Roachford, brings decades of Senate experience working on military installations including Joint Base McGuire-Dix-Lakehurst, reinforcing in-office expertise on defense, base issues, and homeland-security related district priorities. He also voted against the DHS funding bill, stating DHS "doesn't deserve more funding" until it takes concrete steps to rein in abusive ICE agents and submits to stronger congressional oversight to protect communities. Conaway's sworn-in statement and biography highlight his service as a Captain in the U.S. Air Force Medical Corps at McGuire Air Force Base and his long record on Military and Veterans Affairs at the state level, reinforcing his personal and legislative connection to defense, military readiness, and homeland-security issues.

Gill framed border security as a homeland security priority, introducing the REMAIN in Mexico Act to reinstate the Migrant Protection Protocols (Remain in Mexico). He argues the policy reduced illegal crossings, fraudulent asylum claims, and increased deportations, and calls on DHS to implement the 2019 MPP guidance as a step to restore stability and security. He reiterated support for securing the border in a March 2025 press release praising President Trump's Joint Address and credited the administration with prioritizing border security. He also introduced the Somalia Immigration Moratorium Act, arguing that Somalia's lack of reliable identity-management and vetting systems poses national security and public safety risks and that a statutory moratorium is needed to protect national security and fiscal responsibility. In January 2026 he introduced the Student Visa Integrity Act to strengthen national-security screening of foreign students, expand in-person interviews, impose penalties for visa fraud, restrict program transfers, and bar nationals of designated adversarial countries from studying in the U.S., framing visa reforms as necessary to prevent adversaries from being trained at American institutions. In November 2025 he advanced the Expedited Removal of Criminal Aliens Act, which would grant law enforcement broader authority to swiftly detain and remove violent criminal aliens, mandate detention and rapid removal for gang members, terrorists, and those convicted of violent crimes, and would limit certain asylum/withholding protections for those categories—presenting the measure as an urgent homeland security step to remove dangerous foreign actors rapidly. In January 2026 he alleged in Oversight Committee testimony that Somali charities and organizations had funneled American funds overseas to finance Al Shabaab, framed that fraud as a national security threat, and supported DOJ investigations and prosecutions. In March 2025 and again in November 2025 he filed articles of impeachment against Chief Judge James E. Boasberg, arguing the judge's rulings blocking executive immigration actions (including standing in the way of invoking the Alien Enemies Act) undermined the Executive Branch's ability to remove violent foreign gang members (naming Tren de Aragua and MS-13) and therefore compromised national security. He also co-introduced the Foreign Influence Transparency and Accountability Act in May 2025 to address foreign adversaries' influence in higher education, framing undisclosed foreign gifts and contracts from countries like China, Russia, and Iran as national security risks to research, student formation, and institutional integrity and proposing audits and punitive excise taxes to deter malign influence. In July 2025 he voted to pass President Trump's One Big Beautiful Bill, which he says 'secures our border,' funds a border wall, and implements an expanded, accelerated deportation operation—demonstrating support for major homeland-security-focused appropriations and enforcement measures paired with Trump's broader agenda. Gill also characterized the February 26, 2025 House budget resolution as providing necessary funding for what he described as a large deportation campaign, linking budget votes to homeland security and enforcement priorities. On March 11, 2025 he voted for the House continuing resolution that he said would freeze spending levels to avoid a shutdown and allow Republicans to prioritize Trump's reconciliation bill, describing the measure as enabling the administration's deportation and border-enforcement priorities. On October 8, 2025 he introduced the Expedited Removal of Criminal Aliens Act as a House companion to Sen. Ashley Moody's S.1827, explicitly seeking to expand expedited removal beyond existing geographic and temporal restrictions to cover violent criminal aliens, mandate detention and swift removal for gang members, terrorists, and those convicted of violent offenses, and make such individuals ineligible for withholding of removal—framing the statutory change as a tool to give law enforcement faster authority to remove dangerous foreign nationals to protect American communities. In March 2025 he also introduced the Land and National Defense (LAND) Act to ban China and Iran from purchasing U.S. agricultural land by imposing reciprocal restrictions; he characterized 'land security' as integral to national security and argued protecting farmland from adversarial ownership is necessary to safeguard food production and sovereignty. In June 2025 he introduced the Mobilizing Against Sanctuary Cities Act to block federal assistance for one year to jurisdictions that refuse to honor ICE detainers or restrict communication with DHS, framing the measure as an enforcement tool to uphold DHS law-and-order priorities and protect communities from alleged cartel and trafficking threats.

Called for a formal congressional investigation into DHS operations after incidents in Tucson alleging deployment of chemical agents, obstruction of journalists and elected officials, and a broader pattern of aggressive federal tactics during immigration enforcement. Criticized high-profile federal visits and rhetoric that promote militarization of border communities, characterized some federal actions as fearmongering and political theater, and has voted against continued DHS funding while calling for senior-level accountability, including resignation or impeachment of officials deemed responsible. After a recent ICE raid in Tucson where she reports being pushed aside and pepper-sprayed along with her staff, reiterated demands for transparency and accountability and highlighted a Border Patrol raid of a humanitarian aid site that reportedly occurred without a warrant. Cosponsored the Protecting Sensitive Locations Act and Limiting ICE’s National Encroachment Act to reinstate limits on ICE enforcement at sensitive locations and curb overreach. Most recently condemned a Border Patrol raid of the No More Deaths humanitarian aid station on the House floor, alleging agents entered without a warrant and arrested migrants inside, framing such enforcement as unconstitutional and part of a broader pattern of unchecked, cruel tactics against border communities. In a field hearing in Minneapolis she condemned the fatal shooting of Renee Nicole Good by a federal agent, accused ICE of operating lawlessly, criticized a federally-controlled probe that shut out state and local authorities, called for impeachment of Secretary Noem over her response, and urged Congress to stop allocating funds to immigration enforcement until significant reforms are enacted. She also voted against a House DHS appropriations package, stating it dramatically expands ICE funding while simultaneously weakening oversight by cutting key oversight offices and failing to require basic safeguards (e.g., agent identification, mask bans, limits on firearms) and decried the bill as a green light for continued abuses. Most recently reiterated that ICE is "corrupted to the core," called for dismantling the agency, demanded rescission of large DHS/ICE funding allocations (which she said were paid for at the expense of SNAP and Medicaid), and described reforms such as body cameras, mask bans, protections for sensitive locations, and judicial-warrant requirements as the bare minimum. Also called for Congress to fully investigate and hold hearings into a recent fatal shooting by an ICE agent in Minneapolis and to rein in what she described as a rogue, lawless ICE.

Supported funding for the 'Golden Dome Missile Defense System' as part of H.R.1, and backed H.R.1 provisions intended to fund and build President Trump's Border Wall, framing those projects as priorities to protect the country. Additionally co-sponsored and praised passage of the Laken Riley Act (H.R.29), endorsing requirements that ICE immediately detain and remove illegal aliens who commit theft offenses and describing the measure as part of his promise to strengthen law enforcement's ability to secure the border and protect Georgians.
